<!--
    Demo Case 08 - In Progress / Complaint / Critical priority
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the EIGHTH of the 10-case demo dataset; together with
    cases 01 through 07 and cases 09 and 10, it satisfies the AAP
    requirement (Section 0.7.4) of "at least 10 demo cases across all
    six statuses and both case types," and contributes to the dataset
    matrix:

        Case 01 - Draft       / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 02 - Open        / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 03 - In Progress / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 04 - Pending     / General Inquiry / Low
        Case 05 - Resolved    / General Inquiry / High
        Case 06 - Closed      / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 07 - Open        / Complaint       / High
        Case 08 - In Progress / Complaint       / Critical  ## THIS FILE
        Case 09 - Resolved    / Complaint       / High
        Case 10 - Closed      / Complaint       / Critical

    The 10-case dataset thus exercises:
      * Every one of the six statuses (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending,
        Resolved, Closed) - this case populates the In Progress slot for
        the Complaint type
      * Both case types (General Inquiry and Complaint) across the
        full lifecycle - case 08 is the canonical IN PROGRESS COMPLAINT,
        the Complaint-flow analog of case 03 (In Progress General
        Inquiry)
      * All four priorities (Low, Medium, High, Critical) - this case
        is the FIRST of two Critical-priority cases (the other is
        case 10), ensuring the all_cases_by_priority Manager View bar
        chart has a non-empty Critical bar with diverse statuses (one
        actively-worked Critical case at In Progress, one fully-resolved
        Critical case at Closed)

    Lifecycle position - WHY In Progress / Complaint / Critical is meaningful:
      A Complaint case at the In Progress status has traversed
      Draft -> Open -> In Progress. The case_manager has assigned both
      the demo team (assigned_group) and the demo agent (assigned_agent),
      and the agent is now actively investigating the complaint. Critical
      priority is appropriate because complaints frequently warrant
      elevated urgency at the investigation phase; the priority reflects
      organizational impact and business urgency at the time the
      manager triaged the case to In Progress. This case represents the
      "hot work" stage of the complaint lifecycle - the most active and
      time-sensitive phase.

    Role / cross-dependency context (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This case DEPENDS ON (loaded BEFORE this record):
        - The scoped application records under ../../app/
            (sys_app and sys_scope; this case's <sys_scope>/<sys_package>
             reference fields resolve via the source attribute against
             those records)
        - The case table definition at ../../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml
            (this record's <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case</sys_class_name>
             requires the table to exist)
        - All dictionary entries for the case table under
            ../../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_*.xml  (every populated
            field below requires its dictionary entry to be present)
        - All choice records under ../../choices/  (the type=Complaint,
            status=In Progress, and priority=Critical choice values must
            be registered)
        - The auto-numbering record at
            ../../numbers/sys_number_x_[scope]_case.xml  (defines the
            CASE0000001 format; this record's <number/> is intentionally
            empty so the platform auto-generates per that format on
            insert)
        - The role records under ../../roles/  (the
            validate_assigned_agent_membership business rule requires
            the demo agent's role assignments; the demo agent's read
            access requires the x_[scope]_case_agent role and its ACLs)
        - The ACL records under ../../acl/  (table-level and field-level
            ACLs gate read/write access; the "Assigned only" clause
            grants the demo agent visibility because assigned_agent
            equals the demo agent's sys_user)
        - The business rule records under ../../business_rules/
            (set_opened_date fires Before-Insert and populates
            opened_date with gs.nowDateTime();
            validate_assigned_agent_membership fires Before-Update and
            verifies the agent is a member of the assigned_group;
            block_draft_backtransition guards against any future
            attempt to revert to Draft)
        - The state-machine flows under ../../flows/  (specifically
            ../../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml, which governs
            this case's lifecycle; the In Progress -> Resolved
            transition is gated by the validate_resolved_transition
            subflow at ../../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml)
        - ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml  (referenced by
            <assigned_agent>; resolved by user_name lookup)
        - ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml  (referenced
            by <assigned_group>; resolved by name lookup)
        - ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
            (grants the case_agent role to the demo agent so the agent
            can read/write this case via the "Assigned only" ACL clause)
        - The seed script's group-membership creation under
            ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (ensures the demo agent is
            a member of the demo team, satisfying the
            validate_assigned_agent_membership business rule's
            "agent must be a member of group" check)

      This case IS REFERENCED BY (loaded AFTER this record):
        - ../tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_06.xml  (Demo task 06:
            Complaint investigation - status=In Progress, due_date=
            today+7 days; references this case via the case field
            resolved by number lookup)
        - ../tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_07.xml  (Demo task 07:
            Witness interview prep - status=Open, due_date=today+3
            days; references this case via the case field resolved by
            number lookup)
        - ../parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml  (the seed script's
            party table includes both a Person-type party (referencing
            the demo manager as Requester) and an Organization-type
            party (referencing "Synthetic Org Alpha" as Respondent) on
            this case, exercising the polymorphic UI Policy at
            ../../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml)
        - The In Progress -> Resolved transition guard test in
            Validation Gate 2 on a COMPLAINT case: this case is the
            CANONICAL RESOLVE-BLOCKER TEST FOR THE COMPLAINT FLOW.
            The validate_resolved_transition subflow's GlideRecord query
            is `case=current AND status!=Closed`, which returns BOTH
            child tasks (task 06 In Progress and task 07 Open). The
            transition is therefore blocked with the verbatim error
            "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
            (per AAP Section 0.5.5). This verifies the
            complaint_state_machine flow enforces the same task-closure
            rule as the general_inquiry_state_machine flow tested by
            case 03; both flows MUST produce the identical verbatim
            blocking-error message.
        - The case_count_by_status Agent Workspace donut at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml  (this
            case populates the In Progress slice)
        - The all_cases_by_status Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_status.xml  (this case
            populates the In Progress bar)
        - The all_cases_by_type Manager View donut at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml  (this case
            populates the Complaint slice)
        - The all_cases_by_priority Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_priority.xml  (THIS
            CASE PROVIDES ONE OF THE TWO CRITICAL ENTRIES; the other is
            case 10. Without these two cases, the Critical bar would be
            empty or zero, defeating the dashboard's full-spectrum
            priority demonstration.)
        - The cases_opened_30d Manager View single-score widget at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml  (this case is
            included in the count of cases opened within the last 30
            days because opened_date is auto-set to gs.nowDateTime() on
            insert by the set_opened_date business rule)
        - The my_open_cases Agent Workspace list at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml  (when the demo
            agent impersonates and opens the dashboard, this case
            appears in the list because assigned_agent=current user AND
            status NOT IN (Resolved, Closed))

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's ten authoring rules):

      Rule 1 - Synthetic only:
        subject       = "Demo case 08: In Progress (Complaint)"
        description   = "Synthetic In Progress complaint case actively
                         being investigated." (no PII; the synthetic
                         marker word "Synthetic" prefixes the description
                         to make the synthetic nature explicit)
        requester_name  = "Synthetic Requester Eight" (synthetic
                          identifier using the literal word "Synthetic"
                          plus the numeral spelled out for the requester,
                          NOT a real person's name)
        requester_email = "requester-8@example.invalid"
                          (RFC 2606 / BCP 32 reserved .invalid TLD never
                          resolves to a real domain; the local part uses
                          the NUMERAL "8" matching the file numbering,
                          NOT the spelled-out word "eight" - this is a
                          deliberate design choice consistent with the
                          file's idempotent file-name convention and
                          matches the pattern used by case 10
                          (requester-10@example.invalid))

      Rule 2 - No auto-number override:
        The <number/> element is intentionally absent. The auto-number
        engine defined in ../../numbers/sys_number_x_[scope]_case.xml
        generates a CASE0000001-format value on insert per AAP Section
        0.5.7 (the "number" row of the case schema specifies "Auto-
        number" with format CASE0000001 and Read-only constraint).

      Rule 3 - Auto-set opened_date (NO explicit override):
        The <opened_date/> element is intentionally absent. The
        set_opened_date Before-Insert business rule at
        ../../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_opened_date.xml fires on
        record insert and sets opened_date = gs.nowDateTime(). On a
        fresh PDI import this yields an opened_date "now," which:
          (a) places this case correctly in the cases_opened_30d
              single-score widget (since "now" is trivially within 30
              days)
          (b) keeps the demo dataset chronologically realistic relative
              to import time
          (c) avoids any need for explicit date overrides (unlike
              cases 06 and 10, which require explicit dates to make
              the avg_time_to_close widget meaningful for Closed cases;
              In Progress cases have no closed_date and thus contribute
              nothing to that widget anyway)

      Rule 4 - No closed_date In Progress:
        The <closed_date/> element is intentionally absent. The
        closed_date field is auto-set ONLY by the set_closed_date
        Before-Update business rule at
        ../../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_closed_date.xml on the
        Resolved -> Closed transition. Since this case is at In Progress
        (not Closed), closed_date MUST remain null. Setting closed_date
        on a non-Closed case would corrupt the avg_time_to_close
        Manager View widget, which filters on Closed status and
        averages (closed_date - opened_date).

      Rule 5 - Both assignments populated, NO pending_reason:
        assigned_group = "x_[scope]_demo_team"  (mandatory because the
                         case had to traverse Open -> In Progress, and
                         assigned_group is required at Open per AAP
                         Section 0.5.5; the value persists through all
                         subsequent statuses - it is the demo team's
                         responsibility to investigate this complaint)
        assigned_agent = "x_[scope]_demo_agent"  (mandatory because the
                         case is at In Progress, and assigned_agent is
                         required at In Progress per AAP Section 0.5.5;
                         the demo agent IS a member of the demo team
                         per the seed script's group-membership setup,
                         satisfying the validate_assigned_agent_membership
                         business rule's "agent must be a member of
                         group" check)
        pending_reason = (absent / unpopulated)  (In Progress cases never
                         carry a pending_reason; pending_reason is set
                         ONLY when the case transitions In Progress ->
                         Pending, and is cleared by the
                         clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress business
                         rule when the case transitions Pending -> In
                         Progress; this case is at In Progress and has
                         not gone through Pending in this dataset, so
                         pending_reason is unambiguously empty)

      Rule 6 - Choice value precision:
        type     = "Complaint"      (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_type.xml; the second
                   of the two case types; capital C deliberate -
                   "Complaint" not "complaint" or "COMPLAINT")
        status   = "In Progress"    (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml; note the
                   SPACE between "In" and "Progress" - NOT a hyphen
                   ("In-Progress"), NOT an underscore ("In_Progress"),
                   NOT concatenated ("InProgress"); per AAP Section
                   0.5.7 the canonical literal is "In Progress" with
                   exactly one ASCII space)
        priority = "Critical"       (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml; the
                   highest priority; capital C deliberate - "Critical"
                   not "critical" or "CRITICAL"; only choice value with
                   a capital C in the priority vocabulary)
        Note: "Complaint" and "Critical" both begin with capital C; this
        co-occurrence is intentional - the highest-priority Complaint
        case is the most-emphasis test data point in the dashboard
        priority distribution.

      Rule 7 - Zero hardcoded sys_id cross-references (AAP Section
               0.7.2 "NO sys_id literals anywhere"):
        The case's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key,
        which is acceptable per the AAP rule (it is NOT a reference to
        any other record). It is a deterministic 32-character lowercase
        hex value computed at file generation time as the MD5 of the
        idempotent subject "Demo case 08: In Progress (Complaint)" =
        695bc82d928c05520c79c4214f4b44bc - so the Update Set engine
        resolves the same sys_id on every PDI import, making the record
        idempotent and round-trip-safe.

        EVERY cross-reference field below uses the stable human-readable
        lookup key (user_name / name / scope source) as both the
        display_value attribute AND the text content - NOT a hardcoded
        sys_id literal. This matches the convention established by every
        peer file in the scoped Update Set (sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, dictionary/x_[scope]_*, the demo cases 09
        and 10, etc.) and complies with the AAP Section 0.7.2 "NO sys_id
        literals anywhere" rule:
          - <assigned_agent display_value="x_[scope]_demo_agent">
                x_[scope]_demo_agent
            </assigned_agent>  resolves by user_name lookup against
                ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
          - <assigned_group display_value="x_[scope]_demo_team">
                x_[scope]_demo_team
            </assigned_group>  resolves by name lookup against
                ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml
          - <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
                resolves by scope source-name lookup against
                ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml
          - <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">
                x_[scope]
            </sys_package>  resolves by scope source-name lookup against
                the same scope record

      Rule 8 - Scope binding:
        <sys_scope>   binds this case row to the scoped application via
                      the scope source name "x_[scope]" defined in
                      ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml at
                      <source>x_[scope]</source>; the display_value
                      "Case Management" matches the sys_app's human-
                      readable name.
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the additional
                      source="x_[scope]" attribute that is required by
                      the Update Set engine for scope-package binding.
                      Note: the source attribute value "x_[scope]" matches
                      what every peer file uses; it is the scope's
                      <source> field, NOT the scoped application's
                      sys_update_name. This is the convention used
                      consistently across the project's Update Set
                      artifacts (cases 09, 10, all roles, all dictionary
                      entries, all ACLs, etc.).

      Rule 9 - Idempotency anchor:
        The case's idempotent key is <subject> =
        "Demo case 08: In Progress (Complaint)". The companion seed
        script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js ensureCase() helper
        queries x_[scope]_case by subject BEFORE inserting; the
        action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner <x_[scope]_case>
        element ensures the same behavior at Update Set import time.
        Both the action attribute and the deterministic sys_id make
        re-imports on a fresh PDI byte-identical and collision-free.

      Rule 10 - Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element:  <record_update table="x_[scope]_case">
        Inner element: <x_[scope]_case action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"> for
                       idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1
                       round-trip-verification gate (Validation Gate 7).
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the established peer
        convention used by sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, role records, dictionary entries, and
        the demo cases 09 and 10 across the scoped Update Set).

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        ArkCase's CaseFile JPA entity declares ~80 fields including a
        terminal "DRAFT" default status with a queue-handler-driven
        transition to "ACTIVE" on save. ArkCase's lifecycle is
        enforced by the ChangeCaseFileStateService (consulted only as
        semantic reference) plus an Activiti BPMN workflow stack. The
        ServiceNow target collapses this to the user-prompt's 12-field
        schema (number, type, status, priority, subject, description,
        opened_date, closed_date, assigned_group, assigned_agent,
        requester_name, requester_email - plus the optional
        pending_reason for the Pending status). The ArkCase status
        vocabulary ("DRAFT", "ACTIVE", "IN_APPROVAL", "APPROVED") is
        replaced by the user-prompt's six-state vocabulary (Draft, Open,
        In Progress, Pending, Resolved, Closed); this case's "In
        Progress" maps semantically to the ArkCase intermediate-active
        phase but is NOT a direct port of any single ArkCase status
        constant.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - The XML well-formedness check (xmllint with no-output flag)
        returns zero errors.
      - No-PII grep returns zero matches against (john|jane|smith|doe|
        @gmail|@yahoo|@outlook|@hotmail|\.com|\.org|\.net) - the
        synthetic identifiers ("Synthetic Requester Eight",
        "requester-8@example.invalid", "x_[scope]_demo_agent",
        "x_[scope]_demo_team") do not include any PII tokens.
      - Choice-value validation: <type>Complaint</type>,
        <status>In Progress</status>, <priority>Critical</priority> -
        capital C in Complaint and Critical; SPACE in "In Progress".
      - Anti-pattern validation:
          grep -E '<(number|opened_date|closed_date|pending_reason)>'
        returns zero matches (none of these fields are populated for
        an In Progress case).
      - Sys-id-literal validation: only ONE <sys_id> element (the
        case's own primary key); NO sys_id literals appear in any
        reference field's text content or display_value attribute.
      - Resolve-blocker validation: this case has TWO non-Closed child
        tasks (task 06 In Progress and task 07 Open). At runtime, an
        attempted In Progress -> Resolved transition MUST surface the
        verbatim error "All tasks must be closed before resolving this
        case." (per AAP Section 0.5.5). This is functionally equivalent
        to case 03's resolve-blocker test for the General Inquiry flow;
        both flows MUST produce the identical verbatim blocking-error
        message.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim in the
        sys_class_name, sys_update_name, all reference values, and the
        file path; the PDI auto-assigns the actual concrete scope id at
        App Engine Studio creation time, and the Update-Set apply-time
        substitution propagates consistently across all bracketed
        placeholders.

    Key insights specific to this case (case 08):
      1. Case 08 is the canonical In Progress Complaint case; it is the
         Complaint-flow analog of case 03 (In Progress General Inquiry).
      2. THIS CASE IS THE COMPLAINT-FLOW RESOLVE-BLOCKER TEST. Where
         case 03 tests the general_inquiry flow's resolve-blocker, this
         case tests the complaint flow's resolve-blocker. Both flows
         MUST produce the same verbatim error: "All tasks must be
         closed before resolving this case."
      3. THIS CASE IS ONE OF TWO CRITICAL-PRIORITY CASES. The other is
         case 10 (Closed Complaint Critical). Together they ensure the
         all_cases_by_priority bar chart has a Critical bar with both
         an active (In Progress) and terminal (Closed) instance.
      4. The status "In Progress" has a SPACE - not a hyphen, not an
         underscore, not concatenated as "InProgress." Per AAP Section
         0.5.7 and ../../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml.
      5. The priority "Critical" has a capital C - only choice value
         matching "Critical." Not "critical," not "CRITICAL." Per
         ../../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml.
      6. Case 08 has tasks with mixed non-Closed statuses - one In
         Progress (task 06) and one Open (task 07). The
         validate_resolved_transition subflow's GlideRecord query is
         `case=current AND status!=Closed`, so BOTH non-Closed statuses
         count toward the resolve-blocker.
      7. Case 08 has both party types - Person (demo manager as
         Requester) and Organization ("Synthetic Org Alpha" as
         Respondent). This exercises the polymorphic UI Policy at
         ../../ui_policy/x_[scope]_case_party_conditional_fields.xml.
      8. This case appears in the Agent Workspace dashboard's "My Open
         Cases" list when the demo agent impersonates and opens it.
      9. The complaint_state_machine flow vs. general_inquiry_state_machine
         flow: per AAP Section 0.5.5, both flows are functionally
         identical (same transition rules, same blocking error
         messages). The split exists for future per-type customization.
         This case verifies the complaint flow's behavior.
     10. Critical priority is reserved for the most-urgent demo cases.
         This case (Critical In Progress) and case 10 (Critical Closed)
         bookend the Critical-priority demonstration: an actively-worked
         Critical case and a fully-resolved Critical case.
-->
<record_update table="x_[scope]_case">
    <x_[scope]_case action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <assigned_agent display_value="x_[scope]_demo_agent">x_[scope]_demo_agent</assigned_agent>
        <assigned_group display_value="x_[scope]_demo_team">x_[scope]_demo_team</assigned_group>
        <description>Synthetic In Progress complaint case actively being investigated.</description>
        <priority>Critical</priority>
        <requester_email>requester-8@example.invalid</requester_email>
        <requester_name>Synthetic Requester Eight</requester_name>
        <status>In Progress</status>
        <subject>Demo case 08: In Progress (Complaint)</subject>
        <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>695bc82d928c05520c79c4214f4b44bc</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>x_[scope]_case_demo_08</sys_update_name>
        <type>Complaint</type>
    </x_[scope]_case>
</record_update>
